<section xml:id="sect-sym-matrix-quad-form">
  <title>Symmetric and Orthogonal Matrices and Quadratic Forms</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
    <alert>This section needs a lot of work</alert> </p>

    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p> A square matrix <m>A</m> is said to be <term>symmetric</term> if <m>A=A^{\intercal}</m>. </p>
      </statement>

    </definition>

    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The eigenvalues of a symmetric matrix are real.
        </p>
      </statement>


      <proof>
        <p> Let <m>\lambda</m> be an eigenvalue of <m>A</m> with corresponding eigenvector <m>
          \boldsymbol{v}</m> . </p>
        <p>
          <me>
            A \boldsymbol{v} = \lambda \boldsymbol{v}
          </me>
        </p>
        <p> Left multiply by <m>\boldsymbol{v}^{\intercal}</m></p>

        <p>
          <me>
            \boldsymbol{v}^{\intercal} A \boldsymbol{v} = \lambda \boldsymbol{v}^{\intercal} \boldsymbol{v}
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>Take the complex conjugate of the eigenvector equation above: </p>

        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>\overline{\boldsymbol{v}}^{\intercal} A^{\intercal} \amp = \overline{\lambda} \overline {\boldsymbol{v}}^{\intercal} </mrow>
            <mrow>\overline{\boldsymbol{v}}^{\intercal} A \amp = \overline{\lambda} \overline {\boldsymbol{v}}^{\intercal}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>left mulitply by <m>\boldsymbol{v}</m></p>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>\overline{\boldsymbol{v}}^{\intercal} A \boldsymbol{v} \amp = \overline{\lambda} \overline{\boldsymbol{v}}^{\intercal}
              \boldsymbol{v} </mrow>
            <mrow>\overline{\boldsymbol{v}}^{\intercal} \lambda \boldsymbol{v} \amp = \overline{\lambda}
              \overline{\boldsymbol{v}}^{\intercal}
              \boldsymbol{v} </mrow>
            <mrow>\lambda \overline{\boldsymbol{v}}^{\intercal} \boldsymbol{v} \amp = \overline{\lambda}
              \overline{\boldsymbol{v}}^{\intercal}
              \boldsymbol{v}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>so <m>\lambda = \overline{\lambda}</m>, hence it is real. </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>

    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The eigenvectors of a symmetric matrix are orthogonal.
        </p>
      </statement>

    </theorem>


    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p> A square matrix <m>Q=[\boldsymbol{q}_1\;\; \boldsymbol{q}_2\;\;\boldsymbol{q}_3\;\; \cdots\;\;\boldsymbol{q}_n] </m>
          is said to be <term>orthogonal</term> if </p>

        <p>
          <me>
            \boldsymbol{q}_i^{\intercal} \boldsymbol{q}_j = 0
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>for all <m>i \neq j</m>. If in addition that <m>\boldsymbol{q}_i^{\intercal}\boldsymbol{q}_i = 1</m> for all <m>i</m>
          then the matrix is also said to be <term>orthonormal</term>. </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p> If <m>Q</m> is a orthonormal matrix, then <m>Q^{\intercal} = Q^{-1}</m>. </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="sect-orthogonal-transformations">
    <title>Orthogonal
      Transformations</title>

    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p> Let <m>Q</m> be a linear transformation from <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> to <m>
            \mathbb{R}^n</m>. If <m>Q</m> is an orthonormal matrix, then the linear transformation
          is said to be an <term>orthogonal transformation</term>. </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p> Show that the rotational transformation
          given in section 7.10 is an orthogonal transformation.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>Show that</p>
        <p>
          <me>
            Q = \begin{bmatrix}
            \cos \theta \amp -\sin \theta \\
            \sin \theta \amp \cos \theta
            \end{bmatrix}
          </me>
        </p>

        <p> satisfies <m>Q^{\intercal} = Q^{-1}</m>.</p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p> A <term>quadratic form</term> is a polynomial function in <m>x_1, x_2, \ldots, x_n</m>
          such that</p>

        <p>
          <me>
            q(\boldsymbol{x}) = a_1 x_1^2 + a_2 x_2^2 + \cdots a_n x_n^2 + b_{12} x_1 x_2 + b_{13} x_1
            x_3
            +
            \cdots
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>Note
      that a quadratic form can have squared terms and products between only two variables.</p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The following are examples of quadratic forms.</p>

        <p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>4x_1^2 + 7x_2^2 + 4x_1x_2</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>x_1^2 + 4x_2^2 + 9 x_3^2 -2x_1x_2 + 3x_1x_3 + x_2x_3 </m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        <p>And the following are not:</p>
        <p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>x_1^2 + 4x_2^2 + 9x_2+ 3</m>.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>x_1^2 + 4x_2^2 + 3x_3^2 + 2x_1x_2 -3x_1 x_2 x_3 </m>.</p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>A quadratic form can be written as </p>

    <p>
      <me>
        q(\boldsymbol{x}) = \boldsymbol{x}^{\intercal} A \boldsymbol{x}
</me>
    </p>

    <p>for some symmetric matrix <m>A</m> and <m>\boldsymbol{x}=[x_1\;\;x_2 \;\; \cdots \;\; x_n]^{\intercal}</m>.</p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p> Find the matrix <m>A</m> for the quadratic forms above: </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>A \amp= \begin{bmatrix}
              4 \amp2 \\
              2 \amp 7
              \end{bmatrix}
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \boldsymbol{x}^{\intercal} A \boldsymbol{x} \amp = [x_1 \;\; x_2] \begin{bmatrix}
              4 \amp2 \\
              2 \amp 7
              \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix}
              x_1 \\ x_2
              \end{bmatrix}
            </mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = [x_1 \;\; x_2] \begin{bmatrix}
              4x_1 + 2 x_2 \\
              2 x_1 + 7 x_2
              \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 4x_1^2 + 2 x_1 x_2 + 2 x_1 x_2 + 7 x_2^2
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p> And for the second quadratic form: </p>

        <p>
          <me>
            A = \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp -1 \amp 3/2 \\
            -1 \amp 4 \amp 1/2 \\
            3/2 \amp 1/2 \amp 9
            \end{bmatrix}
          </me>
        </p>

      </solution>
    </example>

  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="sect-quad-forms">
    <title>Principle Axes of Quadratic Forms</title>

    <p>For the quadratic form:</p>

    <p><me>
        q(\boldsymbol{x}) = \boldsymbol{x}^{\intercal} A \boldsymbol{x}
</me>
</p>

<p>if <m>A = P D P^{-1}</m> can be written: </p>

<p>
  <me>
      q(\boldsymbol{x}) = \boldsymbol{x}^{\intercal} P D P^{-1} \boldsymbol{x}
  </me>
</p>
      <p>and since <m>A</m> is symmetric then the eigenvectors form an
        orthonormal basis so <m>P^{-1} = P^{\intercal}</m>.
        </p>
    <p>
      <me>
         q(\boldsymbol{x}) =\boldsymbol{y}^{\intercal} D \boldsymbol{y}
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        where <m>\boldsymbol{y}= P^{\intercal} \boldsymbol{x}</m>. Example of ellipse/contour plot. </p>
  </subsection>
</section>